        <name>7.4.1.2 Inverse of a matrix</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Consider \(A={@A@}\), and let \(B={@B@}\) be a possible inverse of \(A\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Find \(AB\) and \(BA\)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div&gt;\(AB= \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;\(BA= \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;div&gt; Equate the elements of \(AB\) to those of \(I={@I@}\) and try to solve the resulting four equations.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;What does your solution tell you about finding an inverse of \(A\)?&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;For \(A={@A@}\), \(B={@B@}\) the products are&lt;/p&gt; 
\[AB={@ta1@}, BA={@ta2@}.\]&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Equating \(AB=I\) yields&lt;/p&gt;
\[a=1, b=0, a=0, b=1/2.\]
&lt;p&gt;This is a contradiction, and hence the matrix \(A\) has no inverse and is said to be a &lt;b&gt;singular matrix&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;A matrix with an inverse is said to be &lt;b&gt;non-singular&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
